'''MIMOS II''' is the miniaturised [[Mössbauer spectrometer]], developed by Dr. Göstar Klingelhöfer at the [[University of Mainz|Johannes Gutenberg University]] in [[Mainz]], [[Germany]], that is used on the [[Mars Exploration Rover]]s ''[[Spirit rover|Spirit]]'' and ''[[Opportunity rover|Opportunity]]'' for close-up investigations on the Martian surface of the mineralogy of iron-bearing rocks and soils.<ref>{{Cite journal |title= The miniaturized Mössbauer spectrometer MIMOS II for extraterrestrial and outdoor terrestrial applications: A status report |author1=Klingelhöfer G. |author2=Bernhardt B. |author3=Foh J. |author4=Bonnes U. |author5=Rodionov D. |author6=De Souza P. A. |author7=Schroder C. |author8=Gellert R. |author9=Kane S. |author10=Gutlich P. |author11=Kankeleit E. |journal= Hyperfine Interactions|volume=144|pages= 371–379|date= 2002|doi=10.1023/A:1025444209059|bibcode=2002HyInt.144..371K}}</ref><ref name=Kling2007>{{cite web |url=http://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/phobosdeimos2007/pdf/7038.pdf |title=THE MINIATURISED MOESSBAUER SPECTROMETER MIMOS II: APPLICATION FOR THE "PHOBOS-GRUNT" MISSION. |author=Klingelhoefer |display-authors=etal |date=2007 }}</ref>
MIMOS II uses a [[Cobalt]]-57 gamma ray source of about 300 mCi at launch which gave a 6-12 hr time for acquisition of a standard MB spectrum during the primary mission on Mars, depending on total Fe content and which Fe-bearing phases are present.<ref name=Kling2003/> Cobalt-57 has a half-life of only 271.8 days (hence the extended measuring times now on Mars after over a decade).
The MIMOS II sensorheads used on Mars are approx 9&nbsp;cm x 5&nbsp;cm x 4&nbsp;cm<ref name=Kling2007/> and weigh about 400g<ref name=Kling2003>{{cite web |url=http://www.lpi.usra.edu/meetings/sixthmars2003/pdf/3132.pdf |title=THE MINIATURIZED MÖSSBAUER SPECTROMETER MIMOS II OF THE ATHENA PAYLOAD FOR THE 2003 MER MISSIONS |author=Klingelhoefer |display-authors=etal |date=2003 }}</ref>
The MIMOS II system also includes a circuit board of about 100g.<ref name=Kling2003/>
